n of terroir and climate, together with dramatic improvements in winemaking techniques, result in wines that are once again winning accolades. James describes important grape varieties and wine styles—from delicate sparkling, to rich fortified, and everything in between—including the varietal blends that produce some of the finest Cape wines. Anchoring his narrative in a rich historical context, James discusses all the major wine regions, from Cederberg to Walker Bay, complete with profiles of more than 150 of the country’s finest producers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Agriculture & Food (see also POLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Agriculture & Food Policy).2bisacsh  a18th century.  a19th centuries.  a19th century.  aafrican wines.  acape colony.  acederberg.  aclimate.  aconstantia.  acooking.  aengaging.  afinest producers.  afinest wine producers.  afood and wine.  afood lovers.  agrapes.  aguide book.  ahistorical context.  ahistory of wine.  ahistory.  ainternational wine scene.  amajor wine regions.  arich fortified wines.  asouth african wines.  asweet wines.  atasting notes.  aterroir.  auseful reference.  avarietal blends.  awalker bay.  awine grapes.  awine lovers.  awine profiles.  awine.  awinemaking techniques.  awines.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052026023840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095483040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520954830423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520954830/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY